[1
Date: 4 Oct 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Nation (Nairobi), 3 Oct 2001 [edited

At least 12 people have died in Meru North district in the past 2 months
after eating contaminated maize.
As a result, more than 17 200 tons of grain worth Sh68 million believed to
be contaminated will be destroyed.
Dr Dietmar Ziegler, the medical superintendent at Maua Mission Hospital,
said the dead were among 24 patients who had been admitted to the hospital
since last August after eating the maize. They had liver complications,
which he attributed to aflatoxin, a toxic chemical [mycotoxin produced by
fungi due to poor grain storage. Dr Ziegler said the patients had initially
shown symptoms of Hepatitis B.
He said results of blood samples taken to the Kenya Medical Research
Institute indicated they contained aflatoxin, a fungal substance which
causes liver inflammation.
He said those visiting the hospital with similar symptoms complained of
high fever, headache and abdominal pains.
The district public health officer, Mr Robert Kitulya, confirmed 40 percent
of maize harvested during the last season from Ndoleli, Tigania East,
Igembe South and Uringo was contaminated. Mr Kitulya said the contaminated
maize was being sold in the local market and warned consumers and farmers
against buying it. He announced the launch of a 2-week joint education
campaign by agricultural and public health officers to sensitize farmers
and consumers on how to identify the contaminated grain.
Mr Kitulya said the contaminated grain had mold or fungus stains and a
bitter taste when cooked. He attributed the contamination to poorly
ventilated storage facilities, adding some farmers stored their maize in
plastic containers which retained moisture.
The officer said some tobacco farmers in the affected areas did not know
how to use and safely handle chemicals. Half of the maize samples collected
from food kiosks and some local markets and which were tested by government
chemists had aflatoxin. Mr Kitulya said 8 of the 16 samples taken for tests
were contaminated. The tests followed an alarm raised by health
institutions in the district after receiving numerous patients suspected to
have consumed the grain.
