[2
Date: 5 Oct 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: NAIROBI, Oct 5, 2001 (Xinhua via COMTEX) [edited

Poisoned Maize Destroyed in Kenya
---------------------------------
Kenya's public health officers have seized and destroyed more than 13 230
kg [of contaminated maize in the Meru District of Central Province the
Daily Nation newspaper reported on Friday. The area public health officer,
Robert Kitulya said that [maize was seized from local markets from where
45 more samples were collected and taken to the government chemist for
further tests.
In the past 2 months, 12 people have died while 12 others [were treated at
a local hospital after consuming maize contaminated with aflatoxin. Kitulya
said a high percentage of the maize harvested in the area could be
contaminated with aflatoxin, a toxic chemical produced by fungi due to poor
grain storage.
"The situation could be worse and we are advising consumers, especially in
the rural areas, to be extra-cautious when buying maize grain or maize meal
even from shops," he said.
Agricultural and public heath officers were also targeting hawkers selling
maize in open-air markets and food kiosks, and advised people to inform his
office of any grain or maize products suspected to be contaminated.
Though only maize in some divisions was affected, the education campaign by
agricultural officers would cover the whole district, he said, calling on
farmers to avoid storing strong agro-chemicals or veterinary drugs in food
[storage areas.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Aflatoxin is one of several mycotoxins produced by different fungi during
development of grain seeds and when grain is stored under conditions of
high moisture and temperature. The authorities acted quickly and appear to
have contained the contaminated seed. What is worrisome is other people may
still be at risk if contaminated grain has been distributed to unsuspecting
people in the normal course of daily life.
Kenyan authorities are to be commended for the education program and for
emphasizing food stuffs must never be stored in areas containing pesticides
and veterinary drugs.
For the first report of this poisoning, see the following URL:
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200110030612.html>
For a follow-up, see the following URL which documents the fatal poisoning
of a family of 4 who died following consumption of food contaminated with
tobacco pesticides:
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200110040521.html> - Mod.DH
[Levels of aflatoxin must have been very high to have resulted in death
within 2 months. Typically aflatoxin affects the liver. Most treatments
consist of removing the contaminated grain/products from consumption and
providing supportive care. Aflatoxin will clear the body fairly rapidly
once the source is removed. - Mod.TG
